369
41:48.840 --> 41:57.000
that can be considered. The CHSH game is an
example of a class of games called non-local games.

370
41:57.000 --> 42:01.440
Here's the setup in general
for a non-local game.

371
42:01.440 --> 42:08.190
We have two players, Alice and Bob, who cooperate as a team, so they either win together
or they lose together.

372
42:08.190 --> 42:14.430
This means that they have no
incentive to act selfishly, so it's essentially the opposite
extreme to zero sum games,

373
42:14.430 --> 42:20.850
which are purely competitive, here the game is purely cooperative.

374
42:20.850 --> 42:24.240
There's a third entity called the referee.

375
42:24.240 --> 42:31.140
The referee isn't a player in the game, but rather the referee
runs the game, and in fact, you can think about the specification

376
42:31.140 --> 42:39.450
of a particular instance
of a non-local game and the specification of a
referee as being equivalent.

377
42:39.450 --> 42:48.420
There's a critically important constraint that's placed on Alice and Bob, which is that once the game starts, they're forbidden from
communicating with one another.

378
42:48.420 --> 42:58.260
They can agree beforehand on
whatever strategy they choose, but no communication
is allowed between them during the game itself.

379
42:58.260 --> 43:06.630
If you like, you can imagine
the game taking place in a secure facility of some sort as if the referee is playing
the role of a detective

380
43:06.630 --> 43:13.080
and Alice and Bob are suspects located in different
rooms in a police station, but another way of
thinking about the setup

381
43:13.080 --> 43:20.550
is that Alice and Bob are
separated by a vast distance and communication is prohibited because the speed of light
doesn't allow for communication

382
43:20.550 --> 43:29.760
to happen quickly enough. If Alice tries to send a
message to Bob for instance, the game will be over by
the time Bob receives it.

383
43:29.760 --> 43:35.940
The way a non-local game
works is that first, the referee asks both
Alice and Bob a question.

384
43:35.940 --> 43:40.950
Alice's question is labeled X and Bob's question is labeled Y.

385
43:40.950 --> 43:49.860
In general, you can think about X and Y as being classical states
from whatever classical states that you like and in the
specific case of the CHSH game,

386
43:49.860 --> 43:53.610
X and Y are bits.

387
43:53.610 --> 43:59.820
Alice and Bob must then provide answers, Alice's answer is labeled A,
and Bob's answer is labeled B,

388
43:59.820 --> 44:08.580
and again, these answers can be viewed as classical states in general and like the questions, they
will be bits in the CHSH game.

389
44:08.580 --> 44:15.389
At this point, the
referee makes a decision, Alice and Bob either win or they lose depending on whether or not
the pair of answers A, B

390
44:15.389 --> 44:23.700
is deemed correct for the
pair of questions X, Y that the referee asked, and I'll say a little bit more
about this in just a moment.

391
44:23.700 --> 44:32.044
First, let's take a
closer look at the referee to understand what it is
that's potentially challenging for Alice and Bob in a non-local game.

392
44:32.044 --> 44:39.330
And what makes a non-local
game potentially challenging is that the referee can use randomness to choose the questions X and Y.

393
44:39.330 --> 44:46.350
That means that Alice
and Bob have uncertainty, they don't know ahead of time what question they're going to be asked, and perhaps more importantly,

394
44:46.350 --> 44:55.560
they don't know what question
the other one received and it's that uncertainty
together with the fact that they can't communicate
that presents the challenge.

395
44:55.560 --> 45:02.760
So, it's similar to the situation where a detective
interrogates two suspects in different rooms, if
the suspects don't know

396
45:02.760 --> 45:09.930
what questions the other one is asked, it's much harder if they're guilty to keep their story straight.

397
45:09.930 --> 45:16.860
Now, I mentioned a short
time ago that the referee makes a determination
that Alice and and Bob have either answered
correctly or incorrectly

398
45:16.860 --> 45:20.610
depending upon the questions
that they were asked.

399
45:20.610 --> 45:28.230
It's assumed that this
determination is made according to some fixed
rule and you can consider any rule that you want,
but whatever it is,

400
45:28.230 --> 45:34.980
it is assumed that Alice
and Bob know the rule, so at least they have a fighting
chance to answer correctly.

401
45:34.980 --> 45:43.530
We'll take a look at the
rule for the CHSH game in a moment, but we could
consider a different rule and we would have a different
example of a non-local game.

402
45:43.530 --> 45:51.240
Some non-local games are interesting and in fact some are quite fascinating in mysterious to this day and
some aren't so interesting,

403
45:51.240 --> 45:54.240
that's just the nature of
the non-local game model.

404
45:54.240 --> 46:01.220
Anyway, these are the two different things that are needed to describe a referee; how exactly are the questions chosen

405
46:01.220 --> 46:06.450
and which answer pairs are correct for each possible question pair.

406
46:06.450 --> 46:12.630
If we have a description
of those two things, then we have a description for the referee and that effectively describes

407
46:12.630 --> 46:16.680
an instance of a non-local game.

408
46:16.680 --> 46:21.330
Now let's take a look at
the CHSH game specifically.

409
46:21.330 --> 46:27.750
The way that the game is
defined or, equivalently, how the referee is defined is as follows;

410
46:27.750 --> 46:36.300
first, as I've already mentioned, the questions and answers are all bits, so the referee sends a bit X
to Alice and a bit Y to Bob,

411
46:36.300 --> 46:43.770
and they each respond with a bit. Alice responds with A
and Bob responds with B.

412
46:43.770 --> 46:50.220
The way the referee chooses
which questions to ask is simple, he chooses
them uniformly at random,

413
46:50.220 --> 47:00.690
so, the pair of questions X, Y is equally likely to be anyone
of the four possibilities, zero, zero, zero, one,
one, zero, and one, one.

414
47:00.690 --> 47:09.180
Finally, the rule that
determines which answers win and which answers lose is
that a pair of answers A, B is correct for the pair of questions X, Y

